\begin{abstract}
To be considered for the 2016 IEEE Jack Keil Wolf ISIT Student Paper Award. We develop the tradeoff between privacy, quantified using local differential privacy (L-DP), and utility, quantified using Hamming distortion, for specific classes of universal memoryless finite-alphabet sources. In particular, for the class of permutation invariant sources (i.e., sources whose distributions are invariant under permutations), the optimal L-DP mechanism is obtained. On the other hand, for the class of sources with \textit{ordered statistics} (i.e., for every distribution $P=(P_1,P_2,...,P_M) \in \mathcal{P}, P_1 \ge P_2 \ge  P_3 \ge \ldots \ge P_M$), upper and lower bounds on the achievable local differential privacy are derived with optimality results for specific range of distortions.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
utility-privacy tradeoff, Differential Privacy, Information Leakage
\end{IEEEkeywords}


\IEEEpeerreviewmaketitle


\section{Introduction}

The differential privacy (DP) framework offers strong guarantees risk of identifying an individual's presence in a database from public disclosures of functions of that database. Guaranteeing a tight a bound on privacy risk often incurs a significant penalty in terms of the usefulness of the published result. In this paper we study this privacy-utility tradeoff in the context of publishing a differentially private approximation of the full data set and measure utility via a distortion measure.
\textit{Local differential privacy} (L-DP) was proposed by Duchi et al.~\cite{Duchi} to study scenarios in which a data collector wishes
to infer a parameter of the (unknown) probability distribution that models a population's data. 
Recently, Kairouz et al.~\cite{Kairouz} found the optimal local differential privacy mechanism for a class of utility functions that satisfy a sub-linearity property and show that the resulting L-DP mechanism has a \textit{staircase property}.  




In many applications the data collector/holder may be required to publish a version of the data itself, but may also know something a priori about the underlying population distribution.

In particular, 
they may know that some values are more likely than others, or may know something about the distribution up to the labeling of the alphabet.

Motivated by these observations, in this paper, we model two memoryless sources classes, namely, a \textit{permutation invariant} class wherein the distributions are invariant to permutations of the alphabet and an \textit{ordered statistics} class wherein for a specific permutation of the alphabet the probabilities are ordered (e.g., for $M$ elements in the sample space, the probabilities $P_1 \ge P_2 \ge \ldots \ge P_M$). We assume that for a given dataset its source class is known but its exact distribution is unknown, and capture this uncertainty by modeling the utility as the minimal Hamming distortion over the source class. As we show in Section \ref{sec:prelims}.\ref{sec:counterexample}, the worst-case distortion over the class does not yield a sub-linear utility in the sense of Kairouz et al.~\cite{Kairouz}.
However, we show that the staircase property still holds for optimal mechanisms for permutation invariant sources. For the ordered statistics class,  staircase mechanisms provide an upper bound upper bound; we further present a novel proof 

to lower bound achievable L-DP risk. This lower bounding technique shows that the output alphabet gradually shrinks as the distortion increases. Our bounds coincide for low privacy (low distortion and high utility) regime, showing again the optimality of staircase mechanisms.

\section{Preliminaries \label{sec:prelims}}
Let the alphabet $\cX$ represent data collected about an individual. As a special case, $\cX$ can be a Cartesian product of other alphabet sets, i.e. $\cX = \prod_{k=1}^{K} \cX_k$, where $\cX_k$ is the set of possible values for $k^{th}$ attribute measured about an individual. Given an individual's data $X \in \cX$, our goal is to find a conditional distribution $Q_{\hX|X}$ that maps the input data $X$ to an output data $\hX$ with same alphabet size as $X$. Our objective is to find a $Q_{\hX|X}$ that is both \textit{privacy preserving} and does not distort the data more than some threshold.

We model the data of individuals being drawn from a distribution $P_X$ on $\cX$, but that particular $P_X$ is not fully known.  Let $\mc{P}$ indicate a subset of probability simplex to which the source distribution $P_X$ belongs. For any $P_X \in \mc{P}$, let $Q_{\hX|X}$, $P_{X,\hX} = P_X Q_{\hX|X}$, and $P_{\hX}$ indicate the mechanism, the joint distribution of input and output data, and the marginal distribution of the output respectively. When it is obvious by context we may drop the subscripts and simply use $P$ and $Q$ instead of $P_X$ and $Q_{\hX|X}$. We write $P_i$ for $P_X(X=i)$  for $i \in \cX$.

We measure the distortion between $X$ and $\hX$ using Hamming distortion, i.e. $d(x,y)=1$ if $x\neq y$, and $d(x,y)=0$ if $x= y$. Hence, for a finite set $\cX$ we can assume $\cX = \hat{\cX} = \{1,2,3,\ldots,M\}$ without loss of generality. The average distortion is then given as $\mathbb{E}_{X,\hX}[d(X,\hX)]$. To indicate the the dependence of the average distortion on the source distribution and the mechanism we write $\mathbb{E}_{P_X, Q_{\hX|X}}[d(X,\hX)]$. For Hamming distortion, the average distortion is $\sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i (1-Q(i|i))$. Thus, we can simplify the $Q$ matrix by defining $D_i = 1-Q(i|i)$ for all $i$. Henceforth, it suffices to consider mechanisms $Q(j|i)$ with the following form:
