\subsection{Sub-linearity and our utility function \label{sec:counterexample}}
One can formulate the optimization problem in \eqref{eq: epsilon_star} as $\max_{Q \in \mc{Q}_\epsilon} U(Q)$ where utility $U(Q) =\min_{P \in \mc{P}} \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_i$, and $\mc{Q}_{\epsilon}$ is the set of all $\epsilon$-differentially private mechanisms. It is shown in \cite{Kairouz} that staircase mechanisms are optimal for sub-linear $U(Q)$ (i.e., $U$'s satisfying $U({\gamma}Q)={\gamma}U(Q)$ and $U(Q_1+Q_2) \le U(Q_1)+U(Q_2)$), but it can be verified through the following examples that $U(Q)$ is not sub-linear for both our source classes. Let $M=2$ and consider two mechanisms with distortions $\{1,0\}$ and $\{0,1\}$.\\

a) $M=2$, $\mc{P} = \{P^{(1)}=(1,0), P^{(2)}=(0,1)\}$.  \\
b) $M=2$, $\mc{P} = \{P^{(1)}=(1,0), P^{(2)}=(0.6,0.4)\}$. \\
Clearly, in both cases $\min_{P\in \mc{P}} \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i \left(D^{(1)}_i + D^{(2)}_i\right) > \min_{P\in \mc{P}} \sum_{i=1}^{M}P_i D^{(1)}_i + \min_{P\in \mc{P}} \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D^{(2)}_i$.










