\section{Ordered Statistics: Proofs of Theorem \ref{theorem:2} \label{sec:ordered2}}
We now prove Theorem \ref{theorem:2}, which provides upper and lower bounds on $\edpopt(\mc{P},D)$ for the class $\mc{P}$ of ordered statistics introduced in Definition \ref{def: ordered statistics source}.
In the following collection of lemmas we prove various aspects of Theorem \ref{theorem:2} including the need for various distortion subsets, the ordering of distortions, and the upper and lower bounds. In particular, as the distortion increases there are specific distortion values at which it is likely that the support of output reduces. The following lemma captures this observation precisely.
\begin{lemma}
For a given integer $k$, no mechanism with at least $k$ all-zero columns can be $(\mc{P},D)$-valid for $D < D^{(k)}$.
\label{lemma: not less than D^k}
\end{lemma}
\begin{IEEEproof}
For any $P \in \mc{P}$, any mechanism with $k$ or more all-zero columns will result in an average distortion $\sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_i$ strictly greater than $\sum_{i=M-k+1}^{M} P_i$ because at least $k$ elements in the set $\{D_i\}_{i=1}^{M}$ that are equal to one. Hence, for $D <  D^{(k)}$, no mechanism with $k$ or more all-zero columns can satisfy the distortion constraint for at least one $P \in \mc{P}$ and thus it is not $(\mc{P},D)$-valid.
\end{IEEEproof}


\begin{lemma}
In order to achieve $\edpopt (\mc{P},D)$, it suffices to consider only those $(\mc{P},D)$-valid mechanisms for which the distortion set $\{D_i\}_{i=1}^{M}$ is sorted in the ascending order, i.e. $D_1 \le D_2 \le \ldots \le D_M$.
\label{lemma: ordering of D_i}
\end{lemma}
\begin{IEEEproof}
Let $Q_{\hX|X} \in \Qopt(\mc{P},D)$, and let $\{D_i\}_{i=1}^{M}$ be a distortion vector which is not necessarily ordered. Consider a mechanism $Q_{T(\hX)|T(X)}$ with $\{D_{T(i)}\}_{i=1}^{M}$ as its corresponding distortion vector, where $T(\cdot)$ is chosen such that $D_{T(1)} \le D_{T(2)} \le \ldots \le D_{T(M)}$. Since the set of elements in each column is the same in both $Q_{\hX|X}$ and $Q_{T(\hX)|T(X)}$, $\edp(Q_{\hX|X}) = \edp(Q_{T(\hX)|T(X)})$. Moreover, $Q_{T(\hX)|T(X)}$ is also a $(\mc{P},D)$-valid mechanism, because $P_1 \ge \ldots \ge P_M$ and $D_{T(1)} \le \ldots \le D_{T(M)}$ imply $\sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_T(i) \le \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_T(i) \le D$. Thus, $Q_{T(\hX)|T(X)} \in \Qopt(\mc{P},D)$, and it suffices to only consider mechanisms that have $\{D_i\}_{i=1}^{M}$ with increasing order.
\end{IEEEproof}
\begin{lemma}
$\edpopt(\mc{P},D)=0$ if and only if $D \ge D^{(M-1)}$.
\label{lemma: smallest D for achieving zero privacy}
\end{lemma}
\begin{IEEEproof}
We show that any mechanism $Q$ with $\edp(Q)=0$ can be $(\mc{P},D)$-valid only for $D \ge D^{(M-1)}$.
Let $Q$ be a mechanism with $\edp(Q)=0$, i.e. all the elements of column $i$ have equal elements $a_i$, $a_i \ge 0$ and $\sum_{i=1}^{M} a_i = 1$. Hence, the corresponding distortion values for $Q$ are $D_i = 1-a_i, \forall i$. Also let $Q'$ be the mechanism with zero elements everywhere except the first column where all its elements are $1$, i.e. $D'_1 = 0$, and $D'_i=1$, for $2\le i \le M$. Obviously, $\edp(Q')=0$.
Since $\forall P \in \mc{P}, P_1 \ge P_2 \ge \ldots \ge P_M$, we have $\sum_{i=2}^{M} P_i = \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D'_i \le \sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_i$. Hence, if $Q$ is $(\mc{P},D)$-valid, i.e $\sum_{i=1}^{M} P_i D_i \le D$ then, $\max_{P \in \mc{P}}\sum_{i=2}^{M} P_i = D^{(M-1)} \le D$.
Conversely, for $D \ge D^{(M-1)}$, $\edpopt(\mc{P},D)=0$ can be achieved with $Q'$ defined above.
\end{IEEEproof}

\begin{remark}
Lemma \ref{lemma: smallest D for achieving zero privacy} proves the second half of Theorem \ref{theorem:3} for $D^{(M-1)} \le D \le 1$.
\label{remark: proof of second half of theorem 3}
\end{remark}
